# Response headers for the production host.
#
# This format is read natively by Cloudflare Pages and by Netlify, so the same
# file works on either without translation. Vite copies public/ verbatim into
# dist/, which is what gets deployed.
#
# The first block is not optional. js-dos runs DOSBox in a worker and reaches
# for SharedArrayBuffer, which browsers only hand out to a cross-origin-isolated
# page. Without these two headers the app loads, renders the whole IDE, and then
# fails the moment anything tries to boot an emulator — so a build and a run
# break while setup, the editor and the file tree all look perfectly healthy.
# `vite.config.ts` sends the same pair to dev and preview; this is that same
# promise kept in production.
#
# require-corp additionally means every subresource must be same-origin (or
# carry CORP). Everything this app loads already is: Monaco's worker and its
# codicon font are bundled, and the DOSBox wasm is served from /emulators/.
# Adding a CDN script, a Google font or a remote image will be blocked outright.
# The rest of this block is defence-in-depth on a site that is already static and
# client-side: no backend, no accounts, and nothing typed here ever leaves the
# browser. None of it is load-bearing the way the isolation pair above is.
#
# HSTS is belt-and-suspenders — the whole `.dev` TLD is HSTS-preloaded, so
# browsers force HTTPS regardless — but the header is correct and carries the
# `preload` directive for this specific host. Permissions-Policy denies the
# device features the app has no use for.
#
# This is the production CSP; the strict form in vite.config.ts must stay in step
# with it. The dev server alone adds 'unsafe-inline' to script-src, for Vite's
# Fast Refresh preamble — a dev-only relaxation that never ships here. Every
# source below was settled by driving a real build under the policy, not by
# guessing:
#   'unsafe-eval'   js-dos's emulators.js evaluates a string as JS at boot — the
#                   build dies at emulator start without it. It does NOT grant
#                   'unsafe-inline', so injected inline <script> and on*= handlers
#                   stay blocked; it opens only the eval sink, which is js-dos's
#                   own bootstrap and never sees user data.
#   blob:           Vite builds instantiate the bundled Monaco and DOSBox workers
#                   from blob URLs.
#   'unsafe-inline' on style-src (Monaco injects styles); on scripts only on the
#                   dev server, never in this production policy — see above.
#   frame-ancestors refuses framing, which COOP does not cover.
/*
  Cross-Origin-Opener-Policy: same-origin
  Cross-Origin-Embedder-Policy: require-corp
  X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff
  Referrer-Policy: strict-origin-when-cross-origin
  Strict-Transport-Security: max-age=31536000; includeSubDomains; preload
  Permissions-Policy: accelerometer=(), autoplay=(), camera=(), display-capture=(), geolocation=(), gyroscope=(), magnetometer=(), microphone=(), payment=(), usb=()
  Content-Security-Policy: default-src 'self'; script-src 'self' 'unsafe-eval' blob:; style-src 'self' 'unsafe-inline'; worker-src 'self' blob:; img-src 'self' data: blob:; font-src 'self'; connect-src 'self' blob: data:; object-src 'none'; base-uri 'self'; frame-ancestors 'none'

# Vite fingerprints everything under /assets/, so these are safe to keep forever.
/assets/*
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=31536000, immutable

# The js-dos runtime is copied out of node_modules under its own plain name and
# is not fingerprinted, so it cannot be cached immutably — a bumped `emulators`
# version would otherwise be invisible to anyone who had already visited. A day
# is long enough to keep the 1.4 MB wasm out of a repeat visit's critical path.
/emulators/*
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=86400
